SIMPLE: surface
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surface
<hw>Sur"face`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See
<er>Sur-</er>, and <er>Face</er>, and cf. <er>Superficial</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The exterior part of anything that has length and
breadth; one of the limits that bound a solid, esp. the upper face;
superficies; the outside; <as>as, the <ex>surface</ex> of the earth; the
<ex>surface</ex> of a diamond; the <ex>surface</ex> of the
body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bright <qex>surface</qex> of this ethereous mold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, outward or external appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vain and weak understandings, which penetrate no deeper than the
<qex>surface</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>V. Knox.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A magnitude that has length and
breadth without thickness; superficies; <as>as, a plane
<ex>surface</ex>; a spherical <ex>surface</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>That part of the side which is
terminated by the flank prolonged, and the angle of the nearest
bastion.</def> <rj><au>Stocqueler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Caustic surface</b></col>, <col><b>Heating
surface</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Caustic</er>,
<er>Heating</er>, etc.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Surface
condensation</b></col>, <col><b>Surface condenser</b></col></mcol>.
<cd>See under <er>Condensation</er>, and <er>Condenser</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Surface gauge</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>an instrument
consisting of a standard having a flat base and carrying an adjustable
pointer, for gauging the evenness of a surface or its height, or for
marking a line parallel with a surface.</cd> -- <col><b>Surface
grub</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the larva of the great yellow
underwing moth (<spn>Triphoena pronuba</spn>). It is often destructive
to the roots of grasses and other plants.</cd> -- <col><b>Surface
plate</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a plate having an accurately
dressed flat surface, used as a standard of flatness by which to test
other surfaces.</cd> -- <col><b>Surface printing</b></col>, <cd>printing
from a surface in relief, as from type, in distinction from <xex>plate
printing</xex>, in which the ink is contained in engraved
lines.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surface</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Surface
<hw>Sur"face</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Surfaced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Surfacing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To give a surface to; especially, to cause to have a smooth or
plain surface; to make smooth or plain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work over the surface or soil of, as ground, in
hunting for gold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surface</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Surface
<hw>Sur"face</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
rise from the depths of a liquid to the surface; <as>as, the submarine
<ex>surfaced</ex> to recharge its batteries</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become known or public; -- said of
information.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To show up, as a person who was in hiding; <as>as,
he absconded with the payroll and <ex>surfaced</ex> in
Argentina</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surface loading</ent>⟦br⟧
